&gt; hello.
&gt;
&gt; i&#39;ve recently read hightower and lesiecki&#39;s book on using ant, junit,
&gt; etc.
&gt; and have started using junit for my projects.  i have noticed that
&gt; checking
&gt; to see if a string, arrays, and other collections objects contain a
&gt; certain
&gt; value is often performed.
&gt;
&gt; has there been consideration in the past to add a type of
&gt; &quot;assertContains()&quot; methods to the Assert class?
&gt;
&gt; it would create easier-to-read and maintain tests than having to
&gt; currently
&gt; do containment checks by writing
&gt;
&gt; if(str.indexOf(keywordStr) &lt; 0) {
&gt; 	fail(&quot;failed.&quot;);
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; or similar checks, and for loops.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; the methods could be something like:
&gt;
&gt; assertContains(String containerString, String searchString)
&gt; assertContains(String[] containerArray, String searchString)
&gt; assertContains(Object[] objectArray, Object searchObject, Class
&gt; objClass)
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; sample usage of the 1st one would be:
&gt;
&gt; containerString = &quot;i love junit and think that everyone should use it.&quot;;
&gt; searchString = &quot;junit&quot;;
&gt;
&gt; assertContains(containerString, searchString);  ==&gt;  test passes
&gt; assertContains(containerString, &quot;weDontNeedTesting&quot;);  ==&gt;  test fails
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; thanks and my apologies if this has already been discussed before (i
&gt; checked the faq and mailing list for &quot;assert contain&quot; but didn&#39;t find
&gt; anything...).
